1 FILE /Users/jonathanmallinger/Documents/Family Tree Maker/Mallinger Family Tree Cleaned Media/Schell's Bush Blockhouse Attack 1780.jpg
2 FORM jpg
2 TITL Schell's Bush Blockhouse Attack 1780
2 _DATE 15 Sep 2010
2 _TEXT Vol. 112 - Issue 1, Wednesday, September 15, 2010   http://www.rsmercu
3 CONC ry.com/pages/articledetailsarch.asp?cat=10&art=8262&iss=225      -   l
3 CONC abeled 1780, family history states summer of 1781   -    SCHELL FAMIL
3 CONC Y VICTORIOUS BATTLE     -         Against Band of Indians and Tories 1
3 CONC 50 Years Ago is Recalled at Little Falls     -         Probably take
3 CONC n from the Rochester "Democrat and Chronicle" August 9, 189
3 CONC 6     -         Little Falls--- in this period of peace and security
3 CONC , it is difficult to imagine that the residents of this section once l
3 CONC ived in constant danger of sudden death, which lurked behind trees an
3 CONC d boulders near their homes and was quickly, as well as fearfully, adm
3 CONC inistered by musket shot, tomahawk and scalping knife.     -         I
3 CONC t was only an century and a half ago that the Mohawk Valley and its en
3 CONC virons were desolated by red raiders and their white allies and the re
3 CONC sidents slaughtered as they sought to defend their loved ones and thei
3 CONC r property. Old time citizens here occasionally hark back to those pio
3 CONC neer days and recall the spirit of courage and sacrifice manifested b
3 CONC y those who helped bring this nation into being. Readers of history, f
3 CONC olks here say, realize that alongside the dangers and difficulties th
3 CONC e pioneers faced, present troubles pale into insignificance
3 CONC .     -         Schell Family Recalled     -       To appreciate the s
3 CONC pirit of the revolutionary patriots it is not necessary to go to the s
3 CONC cenes of triumph at Saratoga or Yorktown, nor to search out the pictur
3 CONC e of acute suffering and privation at Valley Forge, incidents here poi
3 CONC nt out. There is no necessity to go out of this valley in search of he
3 CONC roic epics. The sturdy folk who settled here, building their homes i
3 CONC n spite of natural obstructions and the menace of a savage foe, made t
3 CONC heir lives monuments to courage, faith and perseverance. To emphasiz
3 CONC e this statement one incident is recalled here, which should impress r
3 CONC esidents of Little Falls and vicinity because it transpired so near ho
3 CONC me. It is probably familiar to all students of valley history but ther
3 CONC e are no doubt many who have never heard it before. It concerns Christ
3 CONC ian Schell and his family, early settlers of the Schell's Bush neighbo
3 CONC rhood, near this city.     -         It was August 1781. The resident
3 CONC s of the Schell's Bush section were, for the most part, working in th
3 CONC e fields, but had men on the lookout for Tory and Indian raiders. Thei
3 CONC r worst fears were realized when it was learned that a band of 60 Moha
3 CONC wks and Tories, under the leadership of Donald McDonald, was descendin
3 CONC g upon the little settlement. The inhabitants, with the exception of S
3 CONC chell, his wife and sons, fled to the safety of Fort Dayton at Herkime
3 CONC r. The Schell's however, had prepared for just such an emergency by bu
3 CONC ilding a strong block house of logs, two stories high. The upper stor
3 CONC y projected to permit the inmates to fire perpendicularly upon their a
3 CONC ttackers. There were no windows on the lower floor, but loopholes ha
3 CONC d been placed on all sides. Shell always kept a supply of food, wate
3 CONC r and ammunition in the blockhouse, as he never knew when it would b
3 CONC e necessary to take refuge there.     -         SEIGE BEGIN
3 CONC S     -       When the raiders arrived two of the Schell boys were cap
3 CONC tured, the father, mother and four other sons gained the temporary saf
3 CONC ety of the blockhouse. The Tories and saavages immediately besieged th
3 CONC e little fort, but remained at a safe distance at first because of th
3 CONC e rifle fire. Schell's wife loaded the muskets, which her husband an
3 CONC d sons used with deadly aim.     -         An attempt was made to se
3 CONC t the blockhouse afire, but it failed. Then the Tory, McDonald, bold
3 CONC y ran up and tried to force the door by battering it with a crowbar. H
3 CONC e had cause to regret his recklessness when Schell brought him down wi
3 CONC th a shot. After wounding him, Schell quickly opened the door and drag
3 CONC ged the Tory inside, a prisoner. McDonald had some ammunition on his p
3 CONC erson, which the defenders found useful. With their leader captured, t
3 CONC he enemy ceased the attack for a time. Schell thought that the (---) w
3 CONC ould withdraw and going to the second story, he sang one of his favori
3 CONC te hymns, "A Firm Fortress Is Our Lord."     -         ENEMY FIGHTS HA
3 CONC RDER     -       The enemy did not quit, however. Enraged at the manne
3 CONC r in which the defenders were holding out against them and inflictin
3 CONC g casualties in their rank, they fought harder than ever and charged t
3 CONC he fort. Five of the Indians managed to thrust the muzzles of their fi
3 CONC rearms through the loopholes. It was a critical moment for the littl
3 CONC e garrison, but at this juncture Mrs. Schell displayed quick presenc
3 CONC e of mind to snatch an ax and, with well aimed blows, bent the barrel
3 CONC s of the five muskets. Meantime, her husband and sons poured a stead
3 CONC y fire at the enemy who were, in length, forced to withdraw
3 CONC .     -         ENEMY ROUTED BY STRATEGY     -       Darkness was comi
3 CONC ng on and Schell did not know what devility the savages might undertak
3 CONC e under cover of night, so he resolved to attempt to scare them off b
3 CONC y strategy.     -         Going to the second story, he cried out to h
3 CONC is wife that relief was approaching from Fort Dayton. A few minutes af
3 CONC terward, he again shouted, "Captain Getman, you had better bring you
3 CONC r men up on the left side." As he hoped and prayed, Schell's trick foi
3 CONC led the enemy into thinking a sizable body of troops was approaching i
3 CONC n the dusk from Fort Dayton. The Tories and redskins took to their hee
3 CONC ls to the woods. The markmanship of the Shells was attested by the fac
3 CONC t that the enemy suffered a loss of 11 killed and 6 wounded, while no
3 CONC t a single member of the defending garrison was hurt.     -         Th
3 CONC e Schell's remained in the blockhouse all night and although they wer
3 CONC e on guard against a renewal of the attack, they were not again distur
3 CONC bed. The next day their Tory prisoner was removed to Fort Dayton, wher
3 CONC e he died after an operation.     -         FATHER IS KILLE
3 CONC D     -       The two Schell boys captured in the raid were carried aw
3 CONC ay to Canada but their lives were spared and they returned home afte
3 CONC r the war.     -         Their intrepid father eventually fell victi
3 CONC m to the redskins. He was working in his fields, not far from the bloc
3 CONC k house, with two of his sons, when some Mohawks, who had concealed th
3 CONC emselves in a nearby wheat field, opened fire, killed one of the Schel
3 CONC l boys and fatally wounded the father. The man was taken to the fort
3 CONC , where he succumbed to his wound, but the story of his brave defens
3 CONC e of his home and family still lives here. A marker, erected by the D.
3 CONC A.R. commemorates the heroic deed.                       http://herkim
3 CONC er.nygenweb.net/schell3.html
